---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="MCP Wastes 22,945 Tokens Before Your First Message — LeanCTX"
  description="We measured the actual token cost of Model Context Protocol tool definitions in Cursor. The results are alarming: 72% of your context window is consumed before you even ask a question."
  breadcrumbs={[{ name: 'Home', url: '/' }, { name: 'Blog', url: '/blog/' }, { name: 'MCP Overhead', url: '/blog/mcp-overhead/' }]}>

<article class="section-y">
  <div class="content-grid" style="max-width: 48rem;">

    <header class="animate-entrance" style="margin-bottom: clamp(3rem, 2rem + 3vw, 6rem);">
      <p class="fluid-label text-accent" style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">Research</p>
      <h1 class="font-display fluid-h1 font-bold text-text-bright" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        MCP Wastes 22,945 Tokens<br/>Before Your First Message
      </h1>
      <p class="text-muted" style="font-size: 0.875rem;">
        March 29, 2026 &middot; 6 min read &middot; by Yves Gugger
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="blog-content animate-entrance stagger-1">

      <p>
        We measured the actual token overhead of Model Context Protocol (MCP) tool definitions
        in a real Cursor session. The results fundamentally challenge the assumption that MCP
        is efficient for AI-code communication.
      </p>

      <h2>The Measurement</h2>

      <p>
        A standard lean-ctx MCP server exposes 21 tools. Each tool definition includes a name,
        description, and JSON schema for parameters. We measured the token count of these
        definitions using <code>tiktoken-rs</code> (the same tokenizer OpenAI uses).
      </p>

      <div class="blog-stat-grid">
        <div class="blog-stat">
          <span class="blog-stat-value">22,945</span>
          <span class="blog-stat-label">tokens for tool definitions alone</span>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-stat">
          <span class="blog-stat-value">72%</span>
          <span class="blog-stat-label">of a 32K context window consumed</span>
        </div>
        <div class="blog-stat">
          <span class="blog-stat-value">$0.069</span>
          <span class="blog-stat-label">per message just for tool overhead (GPT-4)</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        That's 22,945 tokens before the user types a single character. On Claude 3.5 Sonnet
        at $3/M input tokens, that's $0.069 per message — just for telling the model which
        tools exist. Over a typical 8-hour coding session with 200 tool calls, that's
        <strong>$13.80 in pure overhead</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2>Why MCP Tool Definitions Are So Expensive</h2>

      <p>
        MCP was designed for flexibility, not efficiency. Each tool definition contains:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Verbose descriptions</strong> — written for human readability, not token economy</li>
        <li><strong>Full JSON Schema</strong> — complete type definitions with descriptions for every parameter</li>
        <li><strong>Redundant information</strong> — the same parameter patterns repeated across similar tools</li>
        <li><strong>No compression</strong> — sent as raw JSON on every request</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        For comparison, Cloudflare's "Code Mode" research found similar patterns: AI tools
        spend the majority of their context budget on protocol overhead rather than actual
        code understanding.
      </p>

      <h2>The Solution: Tool Consolidation</h2>

      <p>
        lean-ctx v2.8.2 introduces <strong>Unified Tool Mode</strong> — consolidating 21 individual
        tools into 4 core tools + 1 meta-tool:
      </p>

      <div class="blog-code">
        <pre><code>Before: 21 tools × ~1,100 tokens each = 22,945 tokens
After:   4 core + 1 meta-tool          =  4,200 tokens

Savings: 18,745 tokens per session (81.7%)</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p>
        The meta-tool (<code>ctx</code>) acts as a router: <code>ctx(tool="session", action="load")</code>
        replaces the dedicated <code>ctx_session</code> tool. The 4 high-frequency tools
        (<code>ctx_read</code>, <code>ctx_shell</code>, <code>ctx_search</code>, <code>ctx_tree</code>)
        keep their own definitions for zero-overhead access.
      </p>

      <h2>Broader Implications</h2>

      <p>
        This isn't just a lean-ctx problem. Every MCP server — GitHub, database tools,
        cloud providers — faces the same overhead. A typical development environment with
        3-4 MCP servers might consume <strong>50,000+ tokens just in tool definitions</strong>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The AI-code communication layer needs a new paradigm. Instead of verbose tool schemas,
        we need:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Compressed tool representations</strong> that convey semantics in fewer tokens</li>
        <li><strong>Tool consolidation</strong> that reduces the number of definitions</li>
        <li><strong>Context-aware loading</strong> that only sends relevant tools per request</li>
        <li><strong>Protocol-level optimization</strong> that eliminates redundancy at the wire format</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        This is what lean-ctx is building: not just a compression tool, but an
        <strong>intelligence layer</strong> that makes AI-code communication fundamentally more efficient.
      </p>

      <h2>Try It Yourself</h2>

      <div class="blog-code">
        <pre><code>cargo install lean-ctx
lean-ctx setup

# Enable Unified Mode for maximum savings
export LEAN_CTX_UNIFIED=1</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p>
        Run <code>lean-ctx gain</code> to see your actual token savings in real-time.
      </p>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .blog-content {
    font-size: clamp(0.9375rem, 0.875rem + 0.2vw, 1.0625rem);
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .blog-content h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 0.8vw, 1.75rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text-bright);
    margin-top: 3rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .blog-content p {
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .blog-content ul {
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
  }

  .blog-content li {
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
  }

  .blog-content li strong {
    color: var(--color-text-bright);
  }

  .blog-content strong {
    color: var(--color-text-bright);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .blog-content code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.875em;
    background: var(--color-surface-2);
    padding: 0.15em 0.4em;
    border-radius: 0.25rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .blog-stat-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .blog-stat-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }

  .blog-stat {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 0.75rem;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    text-align: center;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }

  .blog-stat-value {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 1rem + 1.5vw, 2.5rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    line-height: 1;
  }

  .blog-stat-label {
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-muted);
  }

  .blog-code {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 0.75rem;
    padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .blog-code pre {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .blog-code code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
    background: none;
    padding: 0;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
